column19: this version has been the most often reproduced
column20: notably on the walls of the Lincoln Memorial in Washington. It is named after Colonel Alexander Bliss
column21: stepson of historian George Bancroft. Bancroft asked President Lincoln for a copy to use as a fundraiser for soldiers (see \"Bancroft Copy\" below). However
column22: because Lincoln wrote on both sides of the paper
column23: the speech could not be reprinted
column24: so Lincoln made another copy at Bliss's request. It is the last known copy written by Lincoln and the only one signed and dated by him. Today it is on display at the Lincoln Room of the White House.\n\nFour score and seven years ago our fathers brought forth on this continent
column25: a new nation
column26: conceived in Liberty
column27: and dedicated to the proposition that all men are created equal.\n\nNow we are engaged in a great civil war
column28: testing whether that nation
column29: or any nation so conceived and so dedicated
column30: can long endure. We are met on a great battle-field of that war. We have come to dedicate a portion of that field
column31: as a final resting place for those who here gave their lives that that nation might live. It is altogether fitting and proper that we should do this.\n\nBut
column32: in a larger sense
column33: we can not dedicate -- we can not consecrate -- we can not hallow -- this ground. The brave men
column34: living and dead
column35: who struggled here
column36: have consecrated it
column37: far above our poor power to add or detract. The world will little note
column38: nor long remember what we say here
column39: but it can never forget what they did here. It is for us the living
column40: rather
column41: to be dedicated here to the unfinished work which they who fought here have thus far so nobly advanced. It is rather for us to be here dedicated to the great task remaining before us -- that from these honored dead we take increased devotion to that cause for which they gave the last full measure of devotion -- that we here highly resolve that these dead shall not have died in vain -- that this nation
column42: under God
column43: shall have a new birth of freedom -- and that government of the people
column44: by the people
column45: for the people
column46:
shall not perish from the earth.

Abraham Lincoln
November 19
